shared_text:
Gilford Police Department
January 14 at 4:58 PM ·

Our Sincere Gratitude!!

Ms. Laliberte's high school senior English class (titled Reading & Writing for the Workplace) was tasked with creating a business in order to help students learn real world skills in preparation for one day entering the workforce. Students chose to develop a business that makes wooden flags. As part of that business, students also decided they wanted to show their appreciation for public safety professionals in the community. As a result, the class, at a planned luncheon, presented the Gilford Fire & Police Departments with career-themed flags.

The police flag, presented to Lt. Dustin Parent and SRO Alyssa Raxter, is now being proudly displayed in SRO Raxter's GHS office.

Everyone at GPD would like to express their sincere gratitude to all the students who participated in creating this project, and for taking the time to recognize local public safety professionals in such a unique manner. We are honored to be a part of the Gilford community!!
text:
Gilford Police Department
January 14 at 4:58 PM ·

Our Sincere Gratitude!!

Ms. Laliberte's high school senior English class (titled Reading & Writing for the Workplace) was tasked with creating a business in order to help students learn real world skills in preparation for one day entering the workforce. Students chose to develop a business that makes wooden flags. As part of that business, students also decided they wanted to show their appreciation for public safety professionals in the community. As a result, the class, at a planned luncheon, presented the Gilford Fire & Police Departments with career-themed flags.

The police flag, presented to Lt. Dustin Parent and SRO Alyssa Raxter, is now being proudly displayed in SRO Raxter's GHS office.

Everyone at GPD would like to express their sincere gratitude to all the students who participated in creating this project, and for taking the time to recognize local public safety professionals in such a unique manner. We are honored to be a part of the Gilford community!!

In keeping with Tanger Outlets’ mission of being a good corporation citizen, the TangerKIDS Grant Program supports and serves the future generation by providing funding for schools located near Tanger’s centers. This money will be used next year.

post_text:
Gilford finally has "Five Guys"...not burgers but musicians! For the second year in a row, the same 5 male vocalists had the honor of representing GHS at the annual New England Music Festival, held at The Woodstock Academy in Woodstock, CT March 21-23. These five young men, along with 230 other stellar musicians from around NE, spent 2 1/2 days rehearsing their program with nationally known conductors, ending the weekend with incredible performances.

To earn this honor, students have to perform a prepared piece in a Solo & Ensemble Festival in December, earning scores that, if high enough, get them selected for the Concert Festival. Representing Gilford were senior Ryan Witham (4th year), junior Charles Purcell (3rd year) and sophomores Blake Bolduc, Jonathan Buttrick and Chandler Green (all 2nd year).

Congratulations!

post_text: At GHS, the Pie-A-Teacher auction was held Tuesday and raised over $1900 in under and hour! 35 staff members will get pied in the face the Friday before April break. The money raised is going to "The Doorway" at LRGHealthcare to fight the opioid crisis that has impacted many of our community members in some way. Thanks to our students for giving back to help their community.

The GHS Theatre group was awarded a best production last week at the Regional One-Act Theatre Festival. They will be moving on to the next round at Kingswood Regional High School on April 5 and 6.

Chelsea Sasserson and Anna Cook were awarded superior acting awards.

Meredith Ellis was given a superior costume design award.

Kudos to guest-director Grace McLaughlin for her great work as well.
